                '10board',

                '12board',
                'CollegeID',

                'CollegeCityTier']

                'DOL',
                'Designation',
                'JobCity']

data = raw_data.drop(drop_features+drop_targets, axis=1)

cat_features = list(set(cat_features) - set(drop_features))

2.D Scale GPA to 10 point scale¶

In [21]:
data['collegeGPA'].plot(kind='hist', figsize=(15,5))
Out[21]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fae6673c208>

As we can confirm from the data specifications, some candidates have entered their GPA on a scale of 100 while others have submitted on a scale of 10.
Hence, we standardize all the GPAs to a 10 point scale.

In [22]:
data.loc[data['collegeGPA'] <= 10, 'collegeGPA'] *= 10
In [23]:
data['collegeGPA'].plot(kind='hist', figsize=(15,5))
Out[23]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fae669d31d0>
